The concept of actively ending a life, even in cases of terminal illness, is generally viewed as conflicting with these core familial duties and the traditional reverence for life. Furthermore, there is a strong social sentiment that one should not easily give up on a family member, and the act of hastening death can be perceived as an abandonment of that responsibility. While there is a growing, more modern discourse around the idea of "a dignified death" focusing on high-quality palliative care and avoiding futile, invasive, and painful medical procedures—similar to the concept of "letting go" naturally—the act of active euthanasia remains a sensitive topic that is largely rejected by mainstream cultural norms. Therefore, public sentiment tends strongly toward caution and the belief that the timing of death should not be proactively controlled by humans.

