A government that ensures the basic needs of its citizens—including support during periods of unemployment—is seen as one that aligns with the Confucian ideal of benevolent governance, where the state acts as a protector to maintain social harmony and collective prosperity. Consequently, there is a widespread belief that a system that claims to serve the people must provide a safety net to prevent social instability and hardship. This commitment to social stability as a reflection of good governance leads to a high valuation of such state provisions.

